00:00:30.650 --> 00:00:32.070
- Good afternoon, I'm Vince Resh

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:35.675
and I'm chair of the
Hitchcock Lecture Series

00:00:35.675 --> 00:00:39.610
and I want to welcome you to
the second of two lectures

00:00:39.610 --> 00:00:43.880
that are going to be presented
by our guest this year

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:46.153
and we're very delighted to have her here.

00:00:46.990 --> 00:00:49.870
Dr. Eugenie Scott is a
renowned anthropologist

00:00:49.870 --> 00:00:51.760
and science educator.

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:53.370
She was the executive director

00:00:53.370 --> 00:00:57.640
for the National Center for
Science Education since 1986

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:02.460
and until her retirement in
2014 and as many of you know,

00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:05.930
the center is a nonprofit
organization based in Oakland

00:01:05.930 --> 00:01:07.720
whose stated mission is to defend

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:09.680
the integrity of science education

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:11.850
against ideological interference.

00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:13.440
And for those you that were lucky enough

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:14.630
to hear the lecture yesterday,

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:18.340
she talked very, very
brilliantly about two topics

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:20.880
which are always supposed to
keep out of our conversations,

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:22.064
how science and religion,

00:01:22.064 --> 00:01:25.297
sorry, politics and religion
can influence science.

00:01:25.297 --> 00:01:27.313
And just a brilliant lecture.

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:30.050
She received her BS and MS degrees

00:01:30.050 --> 00:01:32.250
from the University of Wisconsin Milwaukee

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.610
at a pHD in biological anthropology

00:01:34.610 --> 00:01:36.183
from the University of Missouri.

00:01:36.183 --> 00:01:38.470
She's taught at the
University of Kentucky,

00:01:38.470 --> 00:01:41.360
University of Colorado, San Jose State

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:44.100
and California State East Bay.

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:46.030
Now, the National Center
for Science Education,

00:01:46.030 --> 00:01:49.090
Dr. Scott's work centered on
attempts to teach evolution

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:53.050
as simply one of a series of
hypotheses about human origins.

00:01:53.050 --> 00:01:55.310
Such as efforts to teach creation science,

00:01:55.310 --> 00:01:58.470
and intelligent design in
American public schools.

00:01:58.470 --> 00:02:01.690
In 2005, Dr. Scott and her staff worked

00:02:01.690 --> 00:02:04.320
on the side of the
plaintiffs in the well known

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:08.653
Kitzmiller versus Dover
Area School District case.

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:13.940
And the court famously ruled
that intelligent design

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:16.080
was indeed a form of creationism

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:17.260
and therefore it's teaching,

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:19.470
violated the establishment clause

00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:23.620
of the first amendment
of the US Constitution.

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:25.120
Now, the Hitchcock Lecture Series

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:28.860
is quite a well known series has gone on

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:30.970
and there's a detailed history of it

00:02:30.970 --> 00:02:32.680
that I'd recommend that you look at.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:36.520
Likewise, there's a more
detailed biography of Dr. Scott

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:41.140
that you may want to read
after the lecture is over.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:44.920
So I want to conclude with 2010,

00:02:44.920 --> 00:02:47.270
the National Academy of
Science awarded Dr. Scott,

00:02:47.270 --> 00:02:50.820
the public welfare medal for
extraordinary use of science

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:52.590
for the public good.

00:02:52.590 --> 00:02:54.390
Her second lecture which will be given now

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:58.480
is entitled Evolution and
Creationism as Science and Myth.

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:00.930
I also to thank Dr Bill Lineker

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:03.190
who as he's done many times,

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:05.900
explained the meaning of
that second graph up there,

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:08.152
which is one of Darwin's first attempts

00:03:08.152 --> 00:03:11.090
at drawing an evolutionary tree

00:03:11.090 --> 00:03:13.490
or what we now call today a phylogeny.

00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:17.560
So I wish you'd all join me
in welcoming Dr. Eugenie Scott

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:19.270
for her second lecture and certainly,

00:03:19.270 --> 00:03:21.259
we're very lucky to have her here.

00:03:21.259 --> 00:03:23.509
(applause)

00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:25.952
- Thank you.

00:03:25.952 --> 00:03:27.133
Thank you Vincent.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:32.860
It really is such a
high honor to be invited

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:34.203
to be a Hitchcock Lecture.

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:38.027
When I got the letter,
I was just blown away.

00:03:38.027 --> 00:03:40.770
My predecessors in this position

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:43.480
have been such extraordinary scholars

00:03:43.480 --> 00:03:46.357
and internationally known brilliant minds.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:53.780
So because this is such a very high honor

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:56.420
and because it's four
o'clock in the afternoon,

00:03:56.420 --> 00:03:58.363
I'm going to read you a bedtime story.

00:03:59.343 --> 00:04:00.500
(laughs)

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:01.990
Please do not fall asleep

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:06.550
because I have a purpose in mind for this.

00:04:06.550 --> 00:04:09.040
Once upon a time, there
was a steam engine.

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:11.140
It was pulling a train full of toys

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:13.200
and food for the good
little girls and boys

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:15.300
on the other side of the mountain.

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:17.960
Then suddenly, the train stopped.

00:04:17.960 --> 00:04:21.150
Her wheels just wouldn't turn anymore.

00:04:21.150 --> 00:04:24.160
So the clown and the toys started
looking for another engine

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:26.300
to take them over the mountain.

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:28.557
They asked a big passenger train,

00:04:28.557 --> 00:04:30.387
"Please, would you take
us over the mountain

00:04:30.387 --> 00:04:32.029
"for the good little girls and boys?"

00:04:32.029 --> 00:04:34.217
"No," said the passenger train.

00:04:34.217 --> 00:04:37.437
"I am much too grand
for the likes of you."

00:04:37.437 --> 00:04:39.917
Then they saw a powerful freight train.

00:04:39.917 --> 00:04:41.787
"Would you please pull
us over the mountain

00:04:41.787 --> 00:04:43.797
"for the good little boys and girls?"

00:04:43.797 --> 00:04:45.237
"No," said the freight train.

00:04:45.237 --> 00:04:46.997
"I am much too powerful and important

00:04:46.997 --> 00:04:49.090
"to pull the likes of you."

00:04:49.090 --> 00:04:51.180
Then they saw a little old train

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:53.907
and asked if it would pull
them over the mountains.

00:04:53.907 --> 00:04:55.667
"No," said the little little train.

00:04:55.667 --> 00:04:58.577
"I am too old and tired
to go over the mountain.

00:04:58.577 --> 00:05:00.460
"I cannot help you."

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:02.603
The toys didn't know what to do.

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:05.917
Then the little blue engine
came up to them and asked,

00:05:05.917 --> 00:05:07.857
"What is the matter my friends?"

00:05:07.857 --> 00:05:09.127
"Oh, little blue engine,

00:05:09.127 --> 00:05:11.157
"would you please pull
us over the mountain?

00:05:11.157 --> 00:05:12.567
"The good little girls and boys

00:05:12.567 --> 00:05:14.097
"won't have any toys to play with

00:05:14.097 --> 00:05:15.627
"or good food to eat if you don't.

00:05:15.627 --> 00:05:17.270
"Please help us."

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:18.670
The little blue engine explained

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:20.390
that she had never been over the mountain

00:05:20.390 --> 00:05:22.330
and usually, she was just asked

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:24.477
to switch trains in the yard.

00:05:24.477 --> 00:05:26.317
"I'm not very big, but I will try

00:05:26.317 --> 00:05:28.180
"to take you over the mountain."

00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:30.790
So she hitched herself to the train.

00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:32.880
It was a very steep mountain

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:35.823
but the little blue engine
kept saying to herself,

00:05:36.980 --> 00:05:40.470
I think I can, I think
I can, I think I can.

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:42.750
And slowly and with great effort,

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:45.690
they started up the track and at last,

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:47.200
they reached the top of the mountain.

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:49.090
The little train did it.

00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:51.240
Down to the children in
the valley, they went.

00:05:51.240 --> 00:05:53.950
Now the good little girls
and boys would have toys

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:55.570
and good food to eat.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:57.420
The little blue train saying to herself,

00:05:57.420 --> 00:06:00.133
I thought I could, I thought
I could, I thought I could.

00:06:02.180 --> 00:06:04.750
And if you think the
little engine that could

00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:07.983
is about talking steam engines,
you're missing the point.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:11.170
The little engine that could

00:06:11.170 --> 00:06:13.331
is about the importance of perseverance,

00:06:13.331 --> 00:06:17.730
having confidence, being
willing to give it your all.

00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:20.550
It's an American inculturation myth.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:23.096
It's a classic American myth.

00:06:23.096 --> 00:06:25.650
If the Hopis or the Iropish

00:06:25.650 --> 00:06:27.210
were writing a story for children

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:30.200
about getting a train over a mountain,

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:32.720
all the toys would get out of the train

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:34.320
and collectively and cooperatively

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:36.610
push the train over the mountains.

00:06:36.610 --> 00:06:39.253
This is an American enculturation myth.

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:44.440
In the beginning, God
created heaven and earth

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:46.080
and the earth was without form

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:48.930
and void and darkness was
upon the face of the deep.

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:52.030
And the spirit of God moved
upon the face of the waters.

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:55.520
And God said, "Let there be
light," and there was light.

00:06:55.520 --> 00:06:57.870
And God saw the light that it was good.

00:06:57.870 --> 00:07:00.290
And God divided the
light from the darkness,

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:03.370
called the light day and
the darkness he called night

00:07:03.370 --> 00:07:06.780
and the evening and the
morning were the first day.

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:08.727
And God said, "Let there be a firmament

00:07:08.727 --> 00:07:09.827
"in the midst of the waters

00:07:09.827 --> 00:07:12.310
"and let it divide the
waters from the waters,"

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:14.790
And God made the firmament
and divided the waters

00:07:14.790 --> 00:07:17.080
which were under the
firmament from the waters

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:19.520
which were above the
firmament and it was so.

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:21.680
And God called the firmament heaven

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:24.670
and the evening and the
morning where the second day.

00:07:24.670 --> 00:07:26.907
And God said, "Let the
waters under the heaven

00:07:26.907 --> 00:07:28.767
"be gathered together into one place

00:07:28.767 --> 00:07:31.800
"and let the dry land
appear," and it was so.

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:33.870
And God called the dry land earth

00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:36.910
and the gathering together
of the waters, he called seas

00:07:36.910 --> 00:07:39.287
and God saw that it was good and God said,

00:07:39.287 --> 00:07:41.217
"Let the earth bring forth grass,

00:07:41.217 --> 00:07:43.347
"the herb yielding seed and the fruit tree

00:07:43.347 --> 00:07:46.830
"yielding fruit after
its kind," and it was so.

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:50.349
And the evening and the
morning were the third day.

00:07:50.349 --> 00:07:52.890
Well, I suspect you have a
pretty good idea how this ends.

00:07:52.890 --> 00:07:54.750
Most Americans are quite familiar

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:56.480
with the Genesis creation story.

00:07:56.480 --> 00:08:00.500
Day four, God creates the
sun, the moon and the stars.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:03.428
Day five He creates sea
creatures and birds.

00:08:03.428 --> 00:08:06.320
Day six he creates people and mammals.

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:08.940
And all of creation is good.

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:10.490
Things go okay for a while,

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:12.970
but then Adam and Eve are
tempted by the serpent

00:08:12.970 --> 00:08:14.200
and disobey God

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:16.473
and they are driven
from the garden of Eden.

00:08:19.010 --> 00:08:22.640
Now the Genesis story is no
more about talking snakes

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:23.990
than the Little Engine that could

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:26.300
is about talking steam engines.

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:29.580
Both are examples of what
folklorists called myth

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:32.853
and myths are really important.

00:08:33.729 --> 00:08:37.100
One dictionary definition
of myth is falsehood,

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:39.973
but it's not important
whether myths are factual.

00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:43.090
In fact, most of the time they aren't

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:45.840
which doesn't lessen their importance.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.760
Let me surprise you, as a
scientist and a humanist,

00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:50.670
I will say that to a people,

00:08:50.670 --> 00:08:53.013
myths are more important than facts.

00:08:54.023 --> 00:08:57.200
And now I better explain
what it mean by myth.

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:00.160
The study of mythology
crosses many borders.

00:09:00.160 --> 00:09:01.806
Folklore and literature certainly,

00:09:01.806 --> 00:09:04.850
but also sociology and anthropology.

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:09.030
And popular speech again, the
synonym of myth is falsehood.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:10.420
To a folklorist though,

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:12.750
myths are the symbolic representation

00:09:12.750 --> 00:09:15.760
of important cultural values to a people.

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:18.480
They are especially important
in non literate cultures

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:21.890
where cultural values have
to be transmitted orally,

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:25.083
but they also occur in
modern industrial countries.

00:09:26.717 --> 00:09:27.820
They have many purposes.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:30.230
They might explain the
origin of the people

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:33.820
or establish rights to land
or to objects or rituals

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:35.550
for tribe or kin groups.

00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:37.840
Myths may be incorporated into rituals

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:39.980
that remind people of the relationships

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:41.470
of their group to other groups

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:43.704
or relationships within the society.

00:09:43.704 --> 00:09:46.550
They may also be art forms.

00:09:46.550 --> 00:09:48.920
Beowulf, the Odyssey, the Norse editors.

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:52.410
These are all art forms,
but highly mythic.

00:09:52.410 --> 00:09:56.060
They represent values which are important

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:58.360
to the people who have developed them.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:01.480
And they are a way of promoting
the continuity of a culture.

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:04.660
And of course, myths
diffuse from group to group.

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:06.570
They're taken apart, they're rearranged,

00:10:06.570 --> 00:10:09.480
they're synchrotized
with a cultural elements

00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:12.070
just like every other aspect of culture.

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:15.558
But the big takeaway here
is that myths are not false.

00:10:15.558 --> 00:10:19.180
They are representative and
they tell important truths

00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:20.710
about a people.

00:10:20.710 --> 00:10:23.930
Myths are not supposed
to be taken literally.

00:10:23.930 --> 00:10:26.650
You're not supposed to
believe that Ragged Dick

00:10:26.650 --> 00:10:28.430
was a real person.

00:10:28.430 --> 00:10:31.340
Ragged Dick is a character
in a popular series of books

00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:35.450
written by the late 19th
century author Horatio Alger.

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:38.380
Who's heard of Horatio Alger stories?

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:39.930
Practically every hand went up.

00:10:41.610 --> 00:10:44.600
Well, Ragged Dick and his fellow heroes

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:49.220
were plucky poor boys who
through their strong character

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:52.630
and basic decency, managed
to pull themselves up

00:10:52.630 --> 00:10:56.900
from poor levels of society
to the middle class.

00:10:56.900 --> 00:10:59.000
The Horatio Alger myth symbolizes

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.830
a very classic American secular myth,

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:03.340
Rags to Riches.

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:06.520
Anybody can succeed, anybody
can pull themselves up

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:07.750
by their bootstraps

00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:11.590
and this is a very, very
powerful American myth.

00:11:11.590 --> 00:11:14.500
And there are individuals who succeed

00:11:14.500 --> 00:11:18.820
against very remarkably difficult odds.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:22.213
People like Ben Carson or
people like George Soros.

00:11:26.490 --> 00:11:28.950
Actually the statistics will show

00:11:28.950 --> 00:11:32.780
that a movement in the United
States from class to class,

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:35.540
social mobility is
actually less than it is

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:37.740
in much of Europe, but it is nonetheless,

00:11:37.740 --> 00:11:39.640
an American myth that we can do that.

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.530
Periodically over the years,
the Horatio Alger myth

00:11:42.530 --> 00:11:45.100
influences American social welfare policy

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:47.480
where poor and working class individuals

00:11:47.480 --> 00:11:50.320
are expected to bootstrap themselves up

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:52.860
with minimal help from
society and government.

00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:56.430
But no one thinks that
Ragged Dick is a real person.

00:11:56.430 --> 00:11:58.210
Ragged Dick is symbolic.

00:11:58.210 --> 00:12:00.700
The power of myth is its symbolism.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:02.770
It's not true in the literal sense

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:05.933
but it's true in the
meaning that it conveys.

00:12:07.070 --> 00:12:10.120
The little engine that could
and Horatio Alger stories

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:11.960
are mythic narratives that illustrate

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:15.350
American secular values,
the value of individuality,

00:12:15.350 --> 00:12:18.220
hard work, perseverance and
confidence on the one hand

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.550
and the importance of
individual character for success

00:12:21.550 --> 00:12:22.530
on the other.

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:24.524
They're not factual, but they are true

00:12:24.524 --> 00:12:27.980
in that they reflect American values.

00:12:27.980 --> 00:12:30.620
Now, myths are not ordinary narratives.

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:32.410
They themselves are ritualized.

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:34.040
There's a number of language conventions

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:35.990
associated with myths.

00:12:35.990 --> 00:12:38.157
There's often an
introduction that tells you,

00:12:38.157 --> 00:12:40.150
oh, I'm in the land of myth now.

00:12:40.150 --> 00:12:41.160
I'm not supposed to believe

00:12:41.160 --> 00:12:44.014
that there's actually fairy godmothers.

00:12:44.014 --> 00:12:45.841
Once upon a time,

00:12:45.841 --> 00:12:50.841
in the beginning, long, long
ago in a galaxy far away.

00:12:51.229 --> 00:12:53.150
(laughs)

00:12:53.150 --> 00:12:56.110
Myths usually have repetitive elements.

00:12:56.110 --> 00:12:57.950
The toys asked three engines

00:12:57.950 --> 00:12:59.160
and it's the fourth engine

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:02.233
that manages to solve the problem.

00:13:03.230 --> 00:13:05.990
In the other children's
book, The Little Red Hen,

00:13:05.990 --> 00:13:07.580
the hen asks the other animals,

00:13:07.580 --> 00:13:09.790
who will help me plant the wheat?

00:13:09.790 --> 00:13:10.850
Not I, said the pig,

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:11.880
not I, said the cow,

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:12.950
not I, said the dog.

00:13:12.950 --> 00:13:15.633
This repetition is something
that's very common.

00:13:16.478 --> 00:13:19.170
And the morning and the
evening were the first day

00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:22.490
and the morning and the
evening were the second day.

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:24.220
So there are linguistic conventions

00:13:24.220 --> 00:13:27.030
that signal that you are
in the world of myth.

00:13:27.030 --> 00:13:29.330
Another characteristic of
myth that sets it apart

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:30.660
from other narrative is that

00:13:30.660 --> 00:13:34.670
it often deals with supernatural elements.

00:13:34.670 --> 00:13:37.550
Characters or circumstances

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:40.860
that would not be typically encountered.

00:13:40.860 --> 00:13:44.570
Gods or demons or talking steam engines.

00:13:44.570 --> 00:13:47.130
Or as with the Horatio Alger myth,

00:13:47.130 --> 00:13:49.583
rich beneficiaries who appear

00:13:49.583 --> 00:13:50.970
(mumbles)

00:13:50.970 --> 00:13:52.743
To solve the problems for you.

00:13:55.143 --> 00:13:56.130
Until I was preparing this talk,

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:58.720
I never actually looked at
the Horatio Alger books.

00:13:58.720 --> 00:13:59.767
They're awful.

00:13:59.767 --> 00:14:00.780
(laughs)

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:03.360
I can kind of see why nobody
really reads them anymore

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:06.030
but everybody knows the Horatio Alger myth

00:14:06.030 --> 00:14:07.843
because the mythical continues

00:14:07.843 --> 00:14:12.623
even without the representation
in this series of books.

00:14:13.780 --> 00:14:17.230
But what usually happens
in the Horatio Alger books

00:14:17.230 --> 00:14:19.090
is you have this plucky poor boy

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:20.500
who's working very, very hard,

00:14:20.500 --> 00:14:23.500
but he's just a decent,
honest, wonderful person

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:25.567
and this rich man comes along

00:14:25.567 --> 00:14:28.450
and gives him a job and then he succeeds.

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:32.680
Or the rich man comes along
and marries Ragged Dick

00:14:32.680 --> 00:14:33.860
to his daughter or something.

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:35.700
Yeah, like that's gonna happen real often,

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:39.783
but so there are supernatural
things that happen in myths.

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:43.230
So since the topic of tonight is actually

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:45.263
the Creationism and Evolution Issue,

00:14:45.263 --> 00:14:49.313
how does myth relate to
creation and evolution?

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:53.730
Well, Bible scholars have
ascertained that the old testament

00:14:53.730 --> 00:14:58.000
was written over a period of
centuries by many individuals

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.670
and was influenced by many factors.

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:02.100
The two major religions.

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:05.040
There are two major religions
that consider it sacred.

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:07.570
Jews look at Genesis as establishing

00:15:07.570 --> 00:15:10.150
the descendants of Abraham
as the chosen people

00:15:10.150 --> 00:15:13.240
and focus on the promise of
restoration of the Jewish people

00:15:13.240 --> 00:15:14.790
to the promised land.

00:15:14.790 --> 00:15:16.330
Christians have a different focus,

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:19.960
which I'll discuss in more
detail later on in the talk.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:23.220
But what did Genesis signify
to the ancient Hebrews

00:15:23.220 --> 00:15:25.930
rather than to modern Christians and Jews?

00:15:25.930 --> 00:15:28.140
Several Christian and Jewish theologians

00:15:28.140 --> 00:15:30.650
have considered what the
Genesis creation story

00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:34.080
would have meant to the
people who set it down

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:38.360
2,500 to 3000 years ago.

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:39.533
Now, think about this.

00:15:39.533 --> 00:15:42.260
Who were the ancient Hebrews?

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:44.960
They were a pretty small tribe

00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:47.730
in the middle of a very
busy part of the world.

00:15:47.730 --> 00:15:50.210
After all, the geographically
the Middle East

00:15:50.210 --> 00:15:52.310
is this crossroads of three continents.

00:15:52.310 --> 00:15:55.150
So there are a lot of
other tribal groups around

00:15:55.150 --> 00:15:59.760
and the Hebrews were this
little monotheistic dot

00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:03.340
in the middle of all these
polytheistic religions.

00:16:03.340 --> 00:16:08.340
The Syrians, the
Babylonians, the Persians,

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:11.530
the Egyptians, and worst of all,

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:15.420
all of these other, larger,
more powerful entities

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:18.834
periodically conquered the poor Hebrews.

00:16:18.834 --> 00:16:22.630
So you can imagine the
pressure on the Hebrews

00:16:22.630 --> 00:16:24.400
to maintain their monotheism

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:26.770
in the middle of all of this pressure

00:16:26.770 --> 00:16:30.760
from especially conquering
nations to adopt their religion,

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:33.400
to adopt their habits and so forth.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:36.960
Maintaining monotheism
and avoiding syncretism

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:39.190
was the issue for the Hebrews.

00:16:39.190 --> 00:16:42.010
And it's all over the Old Testaments.

00:16:42.010 --> 00:16:44.000
Moses's commandments begin,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.783
thou shalt have no other gods before thee.

00:16:48.810 --> 00:16:51.710
Well, this isn't a big issue
in the 20th and 21st century.

00:16:53.082 --> 00:16:56.100
It wasn't even a big issue
in the eighth century,

00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:59.410
but it was a real big issue
for the ancient Hebrews.

00:16:59.410 --> 00:17:01.300
In the King James
version, it's followed by,

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:05.210
thou shalt not make unto
thee any graven image.

00:17:05.210 --> 00:17:06.220
Although we're not really big

00:17:06.220 --> 00:17:08.470
into graven images these days either,

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:12.730
but historically from the
standpoint of the ancient Hebrews,

00:17:12.730 --> 00:17:15.410
these were things that the
neighbors of the Hebrews

00:17:15.410 --> 00:17:19.500
were doing, the whole
business about the golden calf

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:22.453
when the tablets were being
brought down and so forth.

00:17:23.470 --> 00:17:27.330
Keeping their identity
as the chosen people,

00:17:27.330 --> 00:17:29.940
as the Hebrews as opposed to adopting

00:17:29.940 --> 00:17:33.990
all of these cultural
practices of their neighbors.

00:17:33.990 --> 00:17:36.100
This was the big issue for the Hebrews.

00:17:36.100 --> 00:17:37.360
Now, how do people do this?

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:39.620
How do you keep your identity?

00:17:39.620 --> 00:17:42.060
Well, one way is through myth.

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:46.870
One way is through having
stories, having rituals,

00:17:46.870 --> 00:17:48.770
stories that are embedded into rituals

00:17:48.770 --> 00:17:50.860
that you can pass on to next generations

00:17:50.860 --> 00:17:54.460
that you can use to remind
the people in your group,

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:57.010
in your tribe that this is who we are

00:17:57.010 --> 00:17:58.913
and this is why we are important.

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:03.250
How does the creation story in Genesis

00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:06.253
tell us what was important
to the ancient Hebrews?

00:18:07.100 --> 00:18:09.730
The late Presbyterian
theologian Conrad Hyres

00:18:09.730 --> 00:18:12.050
has I think, a very
interesting perspective

00:18:12.050 --> 00:18:15.300
on what Genesis might have
meant to the ancient Hebrews

00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:18.010
and he views it as a powerful myth

00:18:18.010 --> 00:18:21.000
in this symbolic sense that
I've been talking about myth.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:22.970
To remind the Jews that they were people

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:24.860
who were indeed different
from their neighbors

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:26.980
and better than their neighbors

00:18:26.980 --> 00:18:30.930
because their God was the superior God

00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:34.430
and they were this powerful
God's chosen people.

00:18:34.430 --> 00:18:36.500
The ancient Hebrews distinguish themselves

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:39.150
from the neighbors and kept their identity

00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:41.830
by stressing in Genesis
the power of their God

00:18:41.830 --> 00:18:43.450
over other gods.

00:18:43.450 --> 00:18:46.210
So on day one, God creates light

00:18:46.210 --> 00:18:47.930
and separates light from darkness.

00:18:47.930 --> 00:18:51.853
Thus are the gods of light
and darkness vanquished.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:56.460
On day two, God creates
the heavens and the earth.

00:18:56.460 --> 00:19:00.160
Thus vanquishing sky gods and earth gods.

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:04.410
On day three, God creates the
oceans, lands and vegetation,

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:07.823
thus making sea and vegetation
divinities redundant.

00:19:08.740 --> 00:19:12.230
Day four, God creates
the sun, moons and stars,

00:19:12.230 --> 00:19:14.610
therefore establishing his superiority

00:19:14.610 --> 00:19:17.680
over the deities associated
with those heavenly bodies,

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:19.780
which were of course widely worshiped

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:22.630
by the people surrounding the Hebrews.

00:19:22.630 --> 00:19:24.970
Days five and six, he
takes away the divinity

00:19:24.970 --> 00:19:28.370
of the animal kingdom, and
by creating people specialty,

00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:32.610
he takes away the divine
origin of kings and Pharaohs.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:37.350
Ramesses, you're not the
son of Rah, God created you.

00:19:37.350 --> 00:19:39.330
So our God can whoop your God

00:19:39.330 --> 00:19:41.320
is kind of what this is all about.

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:44.680
The sixth day creation
story establishes Yahweh

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:49.250
as the one true divinity,
superior to all of the other gods.

00:19:49.250 --> 00:19:52.441
The rest of Genesis, which
is largely the Abraham story,

00:19:52.441 --> 00:19:54.740
establishes the special relationship

00:19:54.740 --> 00:19:57.650
between the descendants
of Abraham, the Jews

00:19:57.650 --> 00:20:00.603
and this very powerful omnipotent God.

00:20:01.490 --> 00:20:03.750
So the six-day Hebrew creation story

00:20:03.750 --> 00:20:06.363
also symbolizes the nature of God.

00:20:07.320 --> 00:20:09.060
The Hebrew God was ever present,

00:20:09.060 --> 00:20:11.630
unlike the Sumerians or Mesopotamian gods,

00:20:11.630 --> 00:20:14.020
Yahweh didn't originate from the actions

00:20:14.020 --> 00:20:17.010
of some other god or preexisting force.

00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:20.610
We're familiar with the Greeks whose gods

00:20:20.610 --> 00:20:21.443
had a lineage.

00:20:21.443 --> 00:20:25.080
Aronows begot Cronos, Cronos begot Zeus,

00:20:25.080 --> 00:20:27.427
Zeus begot Athena and
all the rest of them.

00:20:27.427 --> 00:20:30.830
But the Hebrew God just is.

00:20:30.830 --> 00:20:33.310
He's been there since eternity.

00:20:33.310 --> 00:20:35.040
He doesn't have a genealogy.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:37.270
He doesn't even have a biography.

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:38.370
He just is.

00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:41.680
He's this very powerful,
omnipotent individual.

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:44.480
He wills the universe into being

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:47.070
unlike the Mesopotamian or Sumerian gods

00:20:47.070 --> 00:20:49.480
that require preexisting materials

00:20:49.480 --> 00:20:51.730
to be formed into the universe,

00:20:51.730 --> 00:20:54.470
God can just say poof, do it.

00:20:54.470 --> 00:20:56.270
God is moral.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:20:58.410
God knows good and evil.

00:20:58.410 --> 00:20:59.670
The neighboring gods,

00:20:59.670 --> 00:21:01.700
if you really take a
look at the Greek gods,

00:21:01.700 --> 00:21:03.530
which is what we're most familiar with

00:21:03.530 --> 00:21:05.400
probably in our culture,

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:06.710
we don't pay a whole lot of attention

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:08.000
to Sumerian gods anymore,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.150
but we just study Greek mythology.

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:12.740
The Greek gods really seemed to govern

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:15.750
in a universe without purpose or meaning.

00:21:15.750 --> 00:21:19.891
But God is moral, he knows good and evil.

00:21:19.891 --> 00:21:24.300
The universe does have purpose
and meaning to the Hebrews.

00:21:24.300 --> 00:21:26.950
God is not part of nature,
but stands outside of it

00:21:26.950 --> 00:21:30.260
as its creator which again
contest very strongly

00:21:30.260 --> 00:21:33.490
with the more animistic aspects

00:21:33.490 --> 00:21:35.040
of the neighboring polytheists.

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:38.830
Genesis thus best reflects
the Hebrew view of nature

00:21:38.830 --> 00:21:41.030
and of God, but it also represents

00:21:41.030 --> 00:21:42.580
a different view of humankind

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:44.700
and that held by their neighbors.

00:21:44.700 --> 00:21:48.100
God specially creates Adam
and Eve, male and female.

00:21:48.100 --> 00:21:50.555
He created them in his image.

00:21:50.555 --> 00:21:51.950
(mumbles)

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:53.270
So people are special.

00:21:53.270 --> 00:21:55.490
They are moral beings like their creator.

00:21:55.490 --> 00:21:57.550
They have a purpose like their creator.

00:21:57.550 --> 00:21:59.400
They're not just random things

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:01.780
at the whim of idiosyncratic gods

00:22:01.780 --> 00:22:03.810
and of course this is all tied in

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:06.363
with the idea of the Jews
being the chosen people.

00:22:07.463 --> 00:22:10.870
To the ancient Hebrews, then
Genesis is about polytheism

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:13.370
versus monotheism and religious syncretism

00:22:13.370 --> 00:22:15.310
versus cultural independence.

00:22:15.310 --> 00:22:16.960
Genesis is a powerful myth

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:18.900
symbolizing issues of life and death,

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:21.070
importance to the ancient Hebrews.

00:22:21.070 --> 00:22:25.700
It is this mythic symbolism
for modern Christians and Jews.

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:26.750
I'm sorry.

00:22:26.750 --> 00:22:30.150
Genesis has mythic symbolism
for modern Christians and Jews

00:22:30.150 --> 00:22:32.150
for different reasons,
which I will talk about

00:22:32.150 --> 00:22:33.340
a little bit later.

00:22:33.340 --> 00:22:36.084
It's not about talking snakes.

00:22:36.084 --> 00:22:37.750
It's not about...

00:22:37.750 --> 00:22:40.080
It's not meant to be taken literally.

00:22:40.080 --> 00:22:43.520
It's myth with all the power and truth

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:46.783
to a people's culture
that myth represents.

00:22:47.740 --> 00:22:50.290
Genesis certainly isn't about science

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:52.620
and whether humans shared common ancestry

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:54.192
with other organisms.

00:22:54.192 --> 00:22:57.410
But what about myth and
science or myth and evolution?

00:22:57.410 --> 00:23:00.260
You often hear Phillip
Johnson from Boalt Hall

00:23:00.260 --> 00:23:04.560
once said that evolution
is the new myth of America.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:06.590
The new mythology or the myth of evolution

00:23:06.590 --> 00:23:08.300
has replaced the myth of Genesis

00:23:08.300 --> 00:23:11.020
or sciences is the modern mythology, etc.

00:23:11.020 --> 00:23:14.610
Well, what about sciences
myth or evolution as myth.

00:23:14.610 --> 00:23:16.710
In the sense that I've
been using myth obviously

00:23:16.710 --> 00:23:20.823
as a symbolic representation
of the values of a people.

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:24.780
Now, as I did with myth,
I need to define science.

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:26.350
So you at least know what I mean

00:23:26.350 --> 00:23:28.200
when I'm talking about science today.

00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:31.190
You may be surprised
to hear a scientist say

00:23:31.190 --> 00:23:33.173
that science is limited way of knowing.

00:23:34.460 --> 00:23:37.010
It is limited in that we're
only trying to explain

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:38.810
the natural world.

00:23:38.810 --> 00:23:41.030
We're not trying to explain everything

00:23:41.030 --> 00:23:43.550
that human beings are interested in.

00:23:43.550 --> 00:23:47.540
I cannot prove to you
scientifically that Mozart

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:50.190
is better than Madonna or that the Beatles

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:52.130
are better than Bieber.

00:23:52.130 --> 00:23:53.370
Those are not scientists...

00:23:53.370 --> 00:23:57.000
Questions of aesthetics are
certainly not scientific issues

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.130
and there are many other issues

00:23:59.130 --> 00:24:03.010
that need to be resolved,
matters of opinion,

00:24:03.010 --> 00:24:04.990
dealing with values and ideologies.

00:24:04.990 --> 00:24:07.700
They're not going to be
resolved by science either.

00:24:07.700 --> 00:24:10.310
Whether Mr. Kavanaugh should be confirmed

00:24:10.310 --> 00:24:13.560
as a supreme court justice
isn't a matter of science.

00:24:13.560 --> 00:24:16.000
We could use logical arguments,

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.200
we could talk about musical complexity

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:21.200
when talking about the Beatles
or talking about Bieber

00:24:21.200 --> 00:24:24.553
but that's not the same thing as science.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.980
We could look at Mr.
Kavanauh's judicial record

00:24:28.980 --> 00:24:30.928
on some issue or another but that's not...

00:24:30.928 --> 00:24:33.780
The fact that you are using
empirical evidence and logic

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:35.170
doesn't mean you're using science

00:24:35.170 --> 00:24:36.970
because empirical evidence and logic

00:24:36.970 --> 00:24:38.973
is part of critical thinking in general.

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:43.410
I like to think of
science as the application

00:24:43.410 --> 00:24:45.790
of critical thinking, if you will,

00:24:45.790 --> 00:24:47.763
to explaining the natural world.

00:24:49.090 --> 00:24:54.090
So science is limited to
explaining the natural world

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:55.860
and there's a second limitation

00:24:55.860 --> 00:24:58.230
and that is that we're restricted

00:24:58.230 --> 00:25:02.090
to explaining the natural
world through natural processes

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:05.800
and unlike what many people think,

00:25:05.800 --> 00:25:10.800
this limitation of science to
only using natural processes

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:13.710
isn't because all scientists are atheists

00:25:13.710 --> 00:25:14.876
because they aren't.

00:25:14.876 --> 00:25:19.080
It's because the essence of science

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:22.370
is testing our explanations
against the natural worlds.

00:25:22.370 --> 00:25:23.816
And when you think about it,

00:25:23.816 --> 00:25:26.950
how do you test an explanation?

00:25:26.950 --> 00:25:29.570
Notice science communication fans.

00:25:29.570 --> 00:25:31.240
I don't use the word experiment

00:25:32.090 --> 00:25:34.030
because when people hear
the word experiment,

00:25:34.030 --> 00:25:36.250
they think of somebody in
a laboratory doing this

00:25:36.250 --> 00:25:38.520
and they don't think of
these graduate students

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:43.210
in IB out in the field who
may also be doing experiments.

00:25:43.210 --> 00:25:44.980
So I talk about tests

00:25:44.980 --> 00:25:46.560
because there are a lot of different ways

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:48.030
we can test our explanations.

00:25:48.030 --> 00:25:51.420
So the essence of testing an explanation

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:55.040
has to do with holding
constant some variables

00:25:55.040 --> 00:25:57.440
and then letting other variables go

00:25:57.440 --> 00:25:59.963
so you can see whether
your explanation holds.

00:26:01.090 --> 00:26:03.620
Because science is about testing

00:26:03.620 --> 00:26:06.370
because testing is about
holding constant variables,

00:26:06.370 --> 00:26:08.290
we're stuck with natural causes

00:26:08.290 --> 00:26:11.423
because those are the only
kinds we can hold constant.

