My good friend Bill Thwait once suggested

00:26:14.730 --> 00:26:16.620
if we can only invent a theometer,

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:20.390
then we can perhaps test
supernatural explanations

00:26:20.390 --> 00:26:21.930
but we don't have a theometer

00:26:21.930 --> 00:26:24.600
so we're stuck with natural causes

00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:27.543
because those are the kinds
that we can hold constant.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:32.360
So science turns out to be a method

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:34.110
or procedure that one follows

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:37.010
to find out how the natural world works.

00:26:37.010 --> 00:26:41.160
To operate as myth, science
has to reflect important values

00:26:41.160 --> 00:26:42.770
or ideologies of a people.

00:26:42.770 --> 00:26:44.370
So does it?

00:26:44.370 --> 00:26:46.050
Well if you're a scientist,

00:26:46.050 --> 00:26:48.820
and there are some of us in the audience,

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:51.723
you know that there are
values within science.

00:26:52.630 --> 00:26:55.500
There are values you're
supposed to reflect

00:26:55.500 --> 00:26:56.650
if you do science.

00:26:56.650 --> 00:26:57.890
You don't ignore the data

00:26:57.890 --> 00:27:01.064
that disagrees with your explanation.

00:27:01.064 --> 00:27:05.730
You have to be truthful in
reporting your procedures

00:27:05.730 --> 00:27:08.510
and results so you have to be
willing to change your mind

00:27:08.510 --> 00:27:11.060
with new data or theory and so on.

00:27:11.060 --> 00:27:14.050
But that isn't especially
specific to science.

00:27:14.050 --> 00:27:15.896
I would expect the same kinds of values

00:27:15.896 --> 00:27:19.356
from an accountant, frankly.

00:27:19.356 --> 00:27:22.290
Those are values within science.

00:27:22.290 --> 00:27:25.760
They're not values that
science can symbolize.

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:27.460
There is another reason why I don't think

00:27:27.460 --> 00:27:31.090
science makes good myth
and that is that science

00:27:31.090 --> 00:27:33.960
doesn't reflect any particular culture.

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:36.810
When you think about it,
science, this methodology,

00:27:36.810 --> 00:27:38.860
this practice of explaining
the natural world

00:27:38.860 --> 00:27:41.690
through testing occurs in cultures

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:44.090
and people all over the planet

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:47.130
from individualistic cultures
like the United States

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:51.350
to more communitarian
cultures like China or India,

00:27:51.350 --> 00:27:54.083
but they all do science the same way.

00:27:54.970 --> 00:27:57.305
Science doesn't reflect the culture.

00:27:57.305 --> 00:27:59.060
Well, okay.

00:27:59.060 --> 00:28:01.030
The science studies people
will say, yes it does

00:28:01.030 --> 00:28:04.840
but remember, I'm speaking
at a very general level here.

00:28:04.840 --> 00:28:08.350
In general, there are certain
rules you have to follow.

00:28:08.350 --> 00:28:11.320
If you don't test your explanation,

00:28:11.320 --> 00:28:13.600
you're not going to get it
published in Science Magazine

00:28:13.600 --> 00:28:16.750
and PNS and the other outlets.

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:20.900
Your colleagues in science

00:28:20.900 --> 00:28:22.680
aren't going to trust your results

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:26.110
if you don't follow the
rules of collecting data,

00:28:26.110 --> 00:28:29.123
being honest about it, being
open about it, etc, etc.

00:28:32.470 --> 00:28:33.930
Science has values itself

00:28:33.930 --> 00:28:38.930
but science is a very
international kind of behavior,

00:28:40.080 --> 00:28:40.913
if you will.

00:28:40.913 --> 00:28:45.020
So it really doesn't reflect
the values of a culture

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:47.923
or there's no such thing as
the values of all culture.

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:50.490
So because science is a method,

00:28:50.490 --> 00:28:54.160
I don't think it makes very good myth.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:57.230
There is another reason why
science doesn't make good myth

00:28:57.230 --> 00:28:59.663
and that is because science is,

00:29:00.560 --> 00:29:03.115
it's an open ended kind of explanation.

00:29:03.115 --> 00:29:07.220
There's a core group
of scientific concepts

00:29:07.220 --> 00:29:09.870
that we've tested and
tested and tested and tested

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:11.820
and they're really not going to change.

00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:16.710
That the earth goes around the sun.

00:29:16.710 --> 00:29:19.680
Heliocentrism is here to stay.

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:21.910
We're not really going
to test that anymore.

00:29:21.910 --> 00:29:23.130
The earth is spherical

00:29:23.130 --> 00:29:26.460
regardless of what the flat
earthers are saying these days.

00:29:26.460 --> 00:29:28.170
Living things have common ancestors,

00:29:28.170 --> 00:29:29.280
laws of thermodynamics.

00:29:29.280 --> 00:29:31.540
There are things that we
don't change our minds about

00:29:31.540 --> 00:29:32.700
but there's a lot of things

00:29:32.700 --> 00:29:34.710
that we're still trying to figure out

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:37.710
and it's perfectly
acceptable within science

00:29:37.710 --> 00:29:40.300
to change our minds
about our explanations.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:43.413
That's a feature, not a bug.

00:29:45.060 --> 00:29:47.815
A good friend of mine Met
Kurtmel was once asked,

00:29:47.815 --> 00:29:51.020
why did you become a scientist?

00:29:51.020 --> 00:29:55.647
And he wrote, "As an adolescent,
I aspired to lasting fame.

00:29:55.647 --> 00:29:57.267
"I craved factual certainty

00:29:57.267 --> 00:29:59.697
"and I thirsted for a
meaningful vision of human life,

00:29:59.697 --> 00:30:02.227
"so I became a scientist."

00:30:03.830 --> 00:30:06.733
This is like becoming an
archbishop so you can meet girls.

00:30:12.220 --> 00:30:15.100
So science is continually changing

00:30:15.100 --> 00:30:17.700
though again, that doesn't
mean that it's unreliable

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:21.280
because there are these
core concepts of science

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:22.740
that really don't change,

00:30:22.740 --> 00:30:25.770
but the open-endedness, the
changeability of science,

00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:27.970
although it is very valuable

00:30:27.970 --> 00:30:29.727
for understanding the natural world,

00:30:29.727 --> 00:30:32.833
makes science very poor myth.

00:30:34.630 --> 00:30:37.100
Ashley Montagu once described science

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:41.523
as truth without certainty,
which I like that phrase a lot.

00:30:42.770 --> 00:30:45.520
The values and truths of a culture's myth,

00:30:45.520 --> 00:30:48.110
needs stability and continuity.

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:49.520
Science doesn't give you that.

00:30:49.520 --> 00:30:51.570
So science really doesn't make good myth.

00:30:53.140 --> 00:30:55.730
So I would conclude that
science is very good

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:58.720
for explaining the natural
world, but it's lousy myth.

00:30:58.720 --> 00:31:01.510
However powerful and
inspiring science can be,

00:31:01.510 --> 00:31:05.810
it can't in itself produced
culturally sustaining myths.

00:31:05.810 --> 00:31:06.980
Well, what about evolution?

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:08.340
Is it mythical?

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:10.710
Can evolution symbolize a worldview

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:12.480
or values important to us?

00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:14.570
Let's take a look at evolution.

00:31:14.570 --> 00:31:17.020
Evolution is a three part idea.

00:31:17.020 --> 00:31:18.810
There's the big idea of evolution,

00:31:18.810 --> 00:31:21.430
which is that living things
have common ancestors.

00:31:21.430 --> 00:31:23.810
We and all other living
things on the planet

00:31:23.810 --> 00:31:27.080
have descended with modification
from common ancestors.

00:31:27.080 --> 00:31:29.130
There's also the patterns of evolution.

00:31:29.130 --> 00:31:32.659
How did the tree of life split and branch

00:31:32.659 --> 00:31:35.900
and die through time?

00:31:35.900 --> 00:31:39.340
There's also the mechanisms
or processes of evolution.

00:31:39.340 --> 00:31:41.310
The factors that bring about evolution

00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:44.060
and of course these are
things like natural selection,

00:31:44.060 --> 00:31:48.440
nonselective methods, development
and so forth and so on,

00:31:48.440 --> 00:31:50.230
speciation and the like.

00:31:50.230 --> 00:31:53.080
Now, evolution consists of the big idea,

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:54.690
the pattern and the process.

00:31:54.690 --> 00:31:57.610
Let's take a look at each
of these components in turn

00:31:57.610 --> 00:32:00.880
and consider how they work as myth

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:02.830
or whether they could function as myth.

00:32:03.762 --> 00:32:06.146
Well, when we look at
patterns of evolution,

00:32:06.146 --> 00:32:10.080
I think we see very
little mythic inspiration.

00:32:10.080 --> 00:32:12.680
Whether pandas are bears or raccoons

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:14.950
or whether the thanksgiving Turkey

00:32:14.950 --> 00:32:18.140
is descended from a dinosaur
isn't going to be much use

00:32:18.140 --> 00:32:20.422
in symbolizing cultural values.

00:32:20.422 --> 00:32:24.310
So certainly the patterns of
evolution isn't going to work.

00:32:24.310 --> 00:32:26.640
The mechanisms or processes of evolution,

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:29.860
I think we have a little more
possibility for myth here

00:32:29.860 --> 00:32:32.363
especially the concept
of natural selection.

00:32:33.310 --> 00:32:36.460
There's a rather long history of ideology

00:32:36.460 --> 00:32:40.000
seizing on natural selection
to support their views.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:41.810
Capitalists like Andrew Carnegie

00:32:41.810 --> 00:32:43.810
promoted evolution by natural selection

00:32:43.810 --> 00:32:45.480
to promote capitalism.

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:48.010
Henry Russell Wallace was a socialist.

00:32:48.010 --> 00:32:52.160
He supported his views
with natural selection.

00:32:52.160 --> 00:32:54.410
Peter Kropotkin argued for anarchy

00:32:54.410 --> 00:32:56.690
using evolution and natural selection

00:32:56.690 --> 00:32:59.283
and Vernon Kellogg argued for pacifism.

00:33:00.750 --> 00:33:02.700
Now think about that.

00:33:02.700 --> 00:33:04.913
Capitalism, socialism,
anarchy and pacifism.

00:33:06.690 --> 00:33:09.800
These all are inspired
by natural selection.

00:33:09.800 --> 00:33:12.330
It's kind of like the
blind man and the elephant.

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:14.090
They're sort of taking what they want

00:33:14.090 --> 00:33:15.660
to support their particular point of view.

00:33:15.660 --> 00:33:17.788
I think the ideology comes first

00:33:17.788 --> 00:33:21.890
and these men and others following them,

00:33:21.890 --> 00:33:24.600
are taking a powerful scientific idea

00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:28.120
and using it to support their
particular ideological views.

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:30.010
But I don't think
there's anything inherent

00:33:30.010 --> 00:33:32.140
in natural selection that would lead you

00:33:32.140 --> 00:33:35.963
to either capitalism,
socialism, pacifism or anarchy.

00:33:36.950 --> 00:33:39.052
So I would argue that despite efforts,

00:33:39.052 --> 00:33:42.490
natural selection, other
mechanisms of evolution

00:33:42.490 --> 00:33:44.860
don't really work as myth either.

00:33:44.860 --> 00:33:48.070
Well, what about the big
idea of common ancestry?

00:33:48.070 --> 00:33:51.370
Okay, here's where we
get some mythic purchase.

00:33:51.370 --> 00:33:55.030
The idea that we and all living
things have common ancestors

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:58.500
is a very powerful scientific idea

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:01.850
and it's also a very
powerful philosophical idea.

00:34:01.850 --> 00:34:04.700
It also happens to be
scientifically correct

00:34:04.700 --> 00:34:07.830
because given all the
evidence that we have,

00:34:07.830 --> 00:34:11.040
I'd contend that the most
powerful element in evolution

00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:14.110
as mythic is its ability to provide us

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:15.900
a sense of place in the universe,

00:34:15.900 --> 00:34:18.870
a view of where we as human
beings and individuals

00:34:18.870 --> 00:34:21.173
stand relative to everything else.

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:26.520
On the other hand, myths
are often reflective

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:30.960
of moral values and ethical
values in the society

00:34:30.960 --> 00:34:35.100
and common ancestry just
like all the rest of science

00:34:35.100 --> 00:34:38.393
isn't very good as a moral guide.

00:34:40.170 --> 00:34:44.823
Science tells you that coyotes
kill rats and house cats.

00:34:45.720 --> 00:34:48.890
It doesn't tell you whether
that is good or bad.

00:34:48.890 --> 00:34:50.740
As Thomas Henry Huxley said,

00:34:50.740 --> 00:34:53.960
science tells you what
is not what should be.

00:34:53.960 --> 00:34:56.190
If you believe that because
something is natural,

00:34:56.190 --> 00:34:57.480
it is therefore good,

00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:00.150
you need to think that
through a little further.

00:35:00.150 --> 00:35:02.228
Hueman said it even before Huxley.

00:35:02.228 --> 00:35:05.670
Ought does not follow from is.

00:35:05.670 --> 00:35:08.490
